 **Never** ignore an escalation or force the same model to retry without changes. If the implementer said it's stuck, something needs to change.

+## Review Loop Limits
+
+- **Max iterations:** 10 for any review loop (spec compliance or code quality). After 10 iterations with unresolved critical or important issues, escalate to the user.
+- **Minor issues don't block:** Note them in the task completion report but proceed to the next task. Do not loop on minor-only feedback.
+- **Same-issue cap:** If the same issue appears in 3 consecutive review cycles, escalate — the implementer and reviewer disagree on how to fix it.
+
+## Batch Dispatch from Dependency Graph
+
+The controller reads the `## Task Dependency Graph` on plan load and computes parallel batches via topological sort:
+
+- Batch 1: tasks with no dependencies (or all deps already `- [x]`)
+- Batch 2: tasks whose deps are all in Batch 1
+- etc.
+
+The dependency graph determines task ordering. The controller never starts a task before its dependencies are complete. Within a batch, the controller dispatches tasks sequentially by default. Parallel dispatch within a batch is permitted only when the tasks' `**Files:**` lists are fully disjoint — no shared files between any two tasks in the batch. The controller checks file lists before deciding. If any overlap exists, dispatch those tasks sequentially.
+
+The controller waits for the entire batch to complete (all reviews passed) before dispatching the next batch.
+
+## Checkpoint Resume
+
+Plan files live under `docs/superpowers/plans/`, which is globally gitignored. Checkpoints are edits to the plan file in place. The plan file stays in the main tree (where writing-plans created it). The SDD controller runs in the user's session (main tree) and dispatches implementer subagents into the worktree. The controller reads and writes the plan file from the main tree. On resume, the user invokes executing-plans from the main tree with the same plan path.
+
+After all tasks in a batch pass two-stage review and prose cleanup, the controller edits the plan file: flips all `- [ ]` → `- [x]` for each completed task in that batch. No git commit (the file is gitignored). The edit persists on disk.
+
+On resume, executing-plans reads the plan file and skips tasks where all steps are `- [x]`.
+
+Granularity is per-task, not per-step. Subagents either finish a task or fail — there is no useful mid-task resume point.
+
+Only the controller edits the plan file. Subagents never touch it. The controller waits for all tasks in a batch to complete, then flips checkboxes for the batch. This avoids concurrent edits.
+
+## Prose Cleanup Pass
+
+Every task ends with a prose cleanup pass. This is not optional. Run after code-quality review reaches zero critical and zero important findings, before marking the task complete:
+
+1. Strip every comment that restates what the code does (`// Initialize the logger`, `// Return the result`).
+2. Strip AI-obvious phrases — apply `humanizer` patterns. No "ensures proper...", "leverages...", "facilitates...", "serves as...", no significance inflation, no rule-of-three padding.
+3. Rewrite remaining comments, docstrings, and error messages so they sound like a person wrote them. Direct and specific. No filler.
+4. Keep only comments that explain *why* code does something a non-obvious way — a hidden constraint, an invariant, a workaround.
+
+The implementer subagent runs this pass itself before reporting the task complete. The controller does not advance to the next task until the pass is reported as done.
+
+## Pre-Merge User Review
+
+After the final code reviewer approves and before invoking `finishing-a-development-branch`, give the user a ready-to-run diff command so they can review all changes from their own terminal:
+
+```
+To review the full diff before we proceed:
+
+  git diff main...<worktree-branch>
+```
+
+Replace `<worktree-branch>` with the actual branch name. Three-dot (`main...<branch>`) shows only the changes introduced on the branch, even if main has advanced. Use branch-based diff, not path-based (`git -C <worktree-path> diff`).
+
+Wait for the user to confirm before continuing to the finishing skill. If the user requests changes, address them and re-present the diff command.
+
+## Polish Dispatch (End-of-Plan)
+
+After the final code reviewer approves and the user confirms the diff, dispatch the `post-implementation-polish` skill against the full implementation before invoking `finishing-a-development-branch`. The plan header's `**Polish:**` line names the rules the polish subagent loads. Max 3 polish iterations before escalating to the user.
+
